<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<mdscript name="XMP_Arena" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="../../../libraries/md.xsd">
  <!--
    XMultiplayer Arena: proxy spawn/despawn/teleport (Milestone A2).

    Everything in this file is PLAUSIBLE, not VERIFIED, same status as XMP_Telemetry.xml
    (see that file's header and docs/A1-messprotokoll.md for the write-side assumptions,
    which this file reuses via XMP_Telemetry_WriteToPipe).

    THE SINGLE HIGHEST-RISK ITEM IN THIS FILE: reading and parsing inbound JSON.
    MD has no confirmed native JSON/string-parsing capability. XMP_Arena_ExtractField
    below is ONE deliberately isolated helper cue standing in for whatever concrete
    mechanism turns out to work in-game, so that if it needs to be rewritten, it is a
    single, localized change rather than scattered assumptions across this file.
    CANONICAL DESCRIPTION OF THE FALLBACK PLAN (if MD truly cannot parse strings
    like this): docs/A2-messprotokoll.md section 1, two options (one field per
    pipe write, or a "|"-delimited line format), decided only after the first
    in-game test of XMP_Arena_ExtractField, not implemented yet either way.

    Further assumptions specific to this file:
      - md.Named_Pipes signals "OnLineReceived" with the raw received line in
        event.param3 (mirroring the raw-string write side; the API is assumed to be a
        dumb byte/line pipe with no JSON awareness in either direction).
      - Proxy ships are tracked in a dynamically-keyed table $XMP.Proxies.{objectId}
        (MD's `$Var.{$Key}` associative-index pattern, as used for keyed blackboard-style
        data in vanilla scripts).
      - create_ship's `macro` attribute accepts the shipType string sent over the wire
        directly as a macro name/reference (spawn.shipType is set to
        player.entity.macro.name on the sending side, so it is already a macro name).
      - set_object_position accepts both a position and a rotation table in one call,
        per PlanMod.md's explicit call-out of set_object_position as the naive-teleport
        action for A2; if the engine actually needs a separate rotation-setting action,
        that is the second thing to fix after the JSON-parsing assumption above.

    Milestone A3 (Dead Reckoning): naive per-update teleport is replaced by writing
    the latest known truth onto the proxy ship's blackboard and letting
    aiscripts/XMP.ProxyPilot.xml continuously extrapolate and fly toward it; see
    that file's header for the A3-specific assumptions (object.blackboard as the MD
    to AI-script channel, move.to.position/move.stop, the aiscript root shape).
    start_ai_script/stop_ai_script below are assumed action names for attaching/
    detaching an AI-script to/from an object, and start_ai_script is assumed to take
    nested <param name="..." value="..."/> elements to override the AI-script's own
    defaults; unconfirmed like everything else here. Two more A3 additions:
      - XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn now calls an assumed create_pilot/add_pilot action on
        the new proxy before start_ai_script, in case an AI-script cannot fly a
        ship that has no assigned NPC pilot; may turn out unnecessary, see
        aiscripts/XMP.ProxyPilot.xml's header for the fuller reasoning.
      - XMP_Arena_HandleStateUpdate reads an additional linkLatencyMs field the
        agent appends to state_update lines specifically (agent/src/pipeMessage.ts,
        not part of the WebSocket/session wire schema in protocol/), an estimate of
        one-way transit delay for that message. The blackboard's recv-time is
        backdated by this amount, so the AI-script's existing "elapsed = now - recv
        time" extrapolation math automatically implements PlanMod.md A3's
        "Position + Geschwindigkeitsvektor x Latenz" without needing separate
        latency-specific logic in the AI-script itself.

    Milestone A4 (Kampf, PlanMod.md A4): client-side hit detection, server-authoritative
    HP, cosmetic fake projectiles. New assumed actions/events, all unconfirmed like
    everything else in this file, see docs/A4-messprotokoll.md for the full list:
      - set_object_invulnerable: called on every proxy at spawn time. A proxy is
        purely a local visual representation of a REAL ship living in another
        player's game, so it must never take or deal "real" local damage: the
        server is the only authority on what actually happens to it.
      - event_object_attacked (unscoped, fires universe-wide): the local hit
        detection hook. Assumed to still fire even for an invulnerable object (the
        object not being harmable locally is exactly why we need a separate
        notification instead of watching its hull/shield for changes; those never
        move). $XMP.ProxyWireIdByGameId.{event.object.id} is a reverse lookup
        (game object id -> wire objectId, the mirror of $XMP.Proxies) populated at
        spawn time, since event.object is a game object reference, not our wire id.
      - event_object_fired (scoped to player.entity): the local "I just fired my
        weapon" hook, used to build the outgoing fire_event so other clients can
        play a cosmetic effect on our proxy in their games.
      - set_object_hull / set_object_shield: apply the server-authoritative
        hp_state to the player's own real ship (a materially consequential
        operation on the one thing in this whole mod that "really" matters).
      - destroy_object's `explosion` attribute (assumed boolean, defaulting to
        false/silent as already used by XMP_Arena_HandleDespawn since A2): A4
        passes explosion="true" specifically for a combat kill (hp_state hull <= 0),
        so a "player disconnected" despawn and a "ship was destroyed" despawn look
        different to everyone watching, per PlanMod.md A4's "kontrollierte
        Zerstörungssequenz".
      - fire_weapon_cosmetic: plays a visual/audio weapon effect on a proxy with no
        damage component. Deliberately does NOT reproduce the reported origin/
        direction exactly (fires from the proxy's own current position/orientation
        instead); a documented simplification to avoid another layer of nested
        JSON sub-extraction for a purely cosmetic effect; revisit if the visual
        mismatch looks wrong in-game.

    KNOWN, ACCEPTED WEAKNESS (PlanMod.md A4, explicitly not solved for V1): hit
    detection is client-side (whoever's local game registers the hit reports it),
    so at latencies above roughly 100ms a target can visibly be "hit around a
    corner" it had already turned past by the time the attacker's client saw the
    hit locally. No server-side lag compensation exists or is planned for V1; see
    docs/A4-messprotokoll.md and PlanMod.md 0.4/1.3 for the accepted-limitations
    framing this follows.
  -->
  <cues>
    <!--
      Central tuning knobs for aiscripts/XMP.ProxyPilot.xml (PlanMod.md A3
      "Tuning"), gathered here so they can be adjusted in one place without editing
      the AI-script itself; see that file's header for what each one does. Passed
      explicitly to start_ai_script in XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn below rather than
      relying only on the AI-script's own <param> defaults.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_TuningDefaults" instantiate="true">
      <conditions>
        <event_cue_signalled cue="md.Named_Pipes.Reloaded" />
      </conditions>
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.DeadReckoningExtrapolationHorizonSec" exact="1.5" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.DeadReckoningSnapThresholdMeters" exact="500" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.DeadReckoningUpdateTimeoutSec" exact="5" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.DeadReckoningRetargetIntervalSec" exact="0.3" />
          <!-- A4: sent as spawn.maxHull/maxShield (XMP_Arena_AnnounceSpawn below) so
               the server's HP authority (server/src/hpTracker.ts) starts this ship
               at the same values the mod itself considers "full health". Mirrors
               protocol/src/combat.ts's DEFAULT_HULL/DEFAULT_SHIELD (100/100);
               there is no shared source between MD and TS, so keep these two
               numbers in sync by hand if either changes. Flat values for every
               ship type in v1, not yet read from the ship's actual macro stats. -->
          <set_value name="$XMP.CombatDefaultMaxHull" exact="100" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.CombatDefaultMaxShield" exact="100" />
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      Announces our own ship to the rest of the session once telemetry starts, so
      other clients know to spawn a proxy for us. Reuses XMP_Telemetry_WriteToPipe
      (XMP_Telemetry.xml) for the actual write/retry/backoff handling, so this cue
      only has to build the JSON payload. Since A4, also sends maxHull/maxShield
      (XMP_Arena_TuningDefaults above) so the server's HP authority initializes
      this ship's HP from the same "full health" values the mod itself uses,
      rather than falling back to protocol/src/combat.ts's DEFAULT_HULL/
      DEFAULT_SHIELD (which happen to be the same numbers today, but the field
      exists precisely so that no longer has to hold once per-shiptype HP exists).
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_AnnounceSpawn" instantiate="true">
      <conditions>
        <event_cue_signalled cue="md.Named_Pipes.Reloaded" />
      </conditions>
      <actions>
        <do_if value="player.entity.exists and player.entity.isclass.ship">
          <do_all>
            <set_value name="$XMP.Json"
              exact="'{&quot;v&quot;:1,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;spawn&quot;,&quot;seq&quot;:0,&quot;ts&quot;:' + player.age
                + ',&quot;objectId&quot;:&quot;' + player.entity.id + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;shipType&quot;:&quot;' + player.entity.macro.name + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;owner&quot;:&quot;' + player.name + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;maxHull&quot;:' + $XMP.CombatDefaultMaxHull
                + ',&quot;maxShield&quot;:' + $XMP.CombatDefaultMaxShield
                + '}'" />
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Telemetry_WriteToPipe" />
          </do_all>
          <else>
            <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][Arena] no player ship yet, cannot announce spawn'" filter="general" />
          </else>
        </do_if>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      Inbound: fires once per NDJSON line the agent forwards from the relay server
      (another session member's spawn/despawn/state_update). Self-resetting, same
      pattern as XMP_Telemetry_Tick, so it keeps listening for the next line.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_OnReceive" instantiate="true">
      <conditions>
        <event_cue_signalled cue="md.Named_Pipes.OnLineReceived" />
      </conditions>
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxLine" exact="event.param3" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_Dispatch" />
        </do_all>
      </actions>
      <cues>
        <cue name="XMP_Arena_OnReceive_Reset" instantiate="true">
          <conditions>
            <cue_completed cue="parent" />
          </conditions>
          <actions>
            <reset_cue cue="parent" />
          </actions>
        </cue>
      </cues>
    </cue>

    <!-- Reads the "type" field and routes to the matching handler. -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_Dispatch" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'type'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxType" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />
          <do_if value="$XMP.RxType == 'spawn'">
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn" />
          </do_if>
          <do_if value="$XMP.RxType == 'despawn'">
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_HandleDespawn" />
          </do_if>
          <do_if value="$XMP.RxType == 'state_update'">
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_HandleStateUpdate" />
          </do_if>
          <do_if value="$XMP.RxType == 'hp_state'">
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_HandleHpState" />
          </do_if>
          <do_if value="$XMP.RxType == 'fire_event'">
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_HandleFireEvent" />
          </do_if>
          <!-- Anything else (e.g. hit_report, which only ever flows client -> server,
               never back down to a client) is silently ignored: unknown/irrelevant
               commands are dropped, not treated as an error (defensive parsing). -->
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      Extracts the raw JSON value for $XMP.ExtractKey out of $XMP.RxLine into
      $XMP.ExtractValue (as a string; callers convert to number themselves where
      needed). See the file header: this is the single most speculative cue here.

      Bugs found and fixed across two A3 review rounds, all in how the value's
      END position is determined and how it's turned into $XMP.ExtractValue:

      1. Last-field problem: the original logic took min(nextCommaPos, nextBracePos)
         unconditionally. When the extracted field is the LAST property in its
         object (e.g. "owner" in a spawn message), there is no following comma, so
         find_string's "not found" result (-1, assumed) was fed straight into min()
         as if it were a real, very-early position, always winning and truncating
         the value to nothing. Fixed by checking for -1 explicitly and falling back
         to the brace position when no comma follows.

      2. Nested-object problem: position/rotation/velocity values are themselves
         JSON objects ("position":{"x":1,"y":2,"z":3}) with their OWN internal
         commas. The unconditional next-comma search matched the first INNER comma
         (e.g. between x and y) instead of the comma/brace that actually ends the
         whole object, truncating $XMP.RxPositionJson etc. to a fragment like
         '{"x":1', broken input for the sub-extraction that reads x/y/z out of
         it afterwards. Fixed by detecting an object-valued field (its first
         character is '{') and, for those, searching only for the matching closing
         brace, never a comma; this protocol's nested objects never nest further
         (only scalar fields inside), so a plain next-'}' search is exact. The
         closing brace itself is included in the captured substring, since the
         sub-extraction re-parses this exact string and needs its own trailing
         "}" for the same last-field fix to apply to ITS last field (z/qw).

      3. Quote-strip-undoes-fix-2 problem (found in the SECOND A3 review round):
         the quote-stripping replace was applied unconditionally to whatever
         span was captured, including the object branch's result. For a scalar
         string value ("Alice") that correctly strips just its own surrounding
         quotes, but for an object-valued span ({"x":10,"y":20,"z":30}) it ALSO
         stripped the quotes around the nested key names, turning it into
         {x:10,y:20,z:30}. The sub-extraction that reads x/y/z back out of that
         span always searches for a QUOTED key ("x":), so it found nothing at
         all, undoing fix 2 one line later and breaking 100% of position/
         rotation/velocity data. Fixed by only applying the quote-strip in the
         scalar branch; the object branch's span is used as-is, quotes intact.

      Known, pre-existing, NOT fixed here (documented in docs/A3-messprotokoll.md):
      a string VALUE that itself contains a literal '}' or ',' (e.g. a player name
      like "{CoolClan} Alice") still truncates extraction early, since the
      end-boundary search has no concept of quoted-string content; it just finds
      the first '}'/',' character anywhere after the value start. Not exercised by
      A1-A3 (no free-form player-supplied strings flow through yet); relevant from
      A5 on once real player names/chat text do.

      IF YOU CHANGE THE LOGIC BELOW: protocol/tests/helpers/mdExtractFieldSimulation.ts
      is a hand-maintained Node port of this exact algorithm (no shared source,
      since MD isn't runnable outside X4 and so can't be imported/tested directly).
      Update
      that file in lockstep, or protocol/tests/canonical.test.ts's extraction tests
      (including the A4 hit_report/hp_state ones) silently stop reflecting what this
      cue actually does.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractNeedle" exact="'&quot;' + $XMP.ExtractKey + '&quot;:'" />
          <find_string name="$XMP.ExtractKeyPos" exact="$XMP.RxLine" pattern="$XMP.ExtractNeedle" start="0" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractValueStart" exact="$XMP.ExtractKeyPos + $XMP.ExtractNeedle.length" />

          <do_if value="$XMP.RxLine.{substring: $XMP.ExtractValueStart, $XMP.ExtractValueStart + 1} == '{'">
            <do_all>
              <find_string name="$XMP.ExtractBracePos" exact="$XMP.RxLine" pattern="'}'" start="$XMP.ExtractValueStart" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractEnd" exact="$XMP.ExtractBracePos + 1" />
              <!-- Object branch: no quote-strip. The span (e.g. {"x":10,"y":20,"z":30})
                   is used verbatim, so the sub-extraction's own quoted-key search
                   ("x":, "y":, ...) still finds its needles. -->
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractValue" exact="$XMP.RxLine.{substring: $XMP.ExtractValueStart, $XMP.ExtractEnd}" />
            </do_all>
            <else>
              <do_all>
                <find_string name="$XMP.ExtractCommaPos" exact="$XMP.RxLine" pattern="','" start="$XMP.ExtractValueStart" />
                <find_string name="$XMP.ExtractBracePos" exact="$XMP.RxLine" pattern="'}'" start="$XMP.ExtractValueStart" />
                <do_if value="$XMP.ExtractCommaPos == -1">
                  <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractEnd" exact="$XMP.ExtractBracePos" />
                  <else>
                    <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractEnd" exact="min{value1=$XMP.ExtractCommaPos, value2=$XMP.ExtractBracePos}" />
                  </else>
                </do_if>
                <!-- Scalar branch only: strip the value's own surrounding quotes
                     (a quoted string becomes bare; a bare number is unaffected). -->
                <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractValue"
                  exact="$XMP.RxLine.{substring: $XMP.ExtractValueStart, $XMP.ExtractEnd}.{replace: '&quot;', ''}" />
              </do_all>
            </else>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      Creates a proxy ship for a remote player's spawn and remembers it keyed by
      objectId, so later state_update/despawn messages for the same objectId can
      find it again. Naive placement at the local player's own position for now;
      the very next state_update for this objectId will move it toward the right
      place. Since A3: also seeds the proxy's blackboard (so the AI-script's first
      loop iteration has valid data, treating "no movement yet" as the initial
      truth), assigns a pilot, and starts XMP.ProxyPilot.xml on it.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'objectId'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxObjectId" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'shipType'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxShipType" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'owner'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxOwner" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <do_if value="not $XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.exists">
            <do_all>
              <create_ship name="$XMP.NewProxyShip" macro="$XMP.RxShipType" position="player.entity.position" owner="player" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}" exact="$XMP.NewProxyShip" />
              <!-- Reverse lookup (game object -> wire objectId), needed by
                   XMP_Arena_OnProxyAttacked (A4): a combat event exposes the game
                   object that was hit, not our own wire-protocol id for it. -->
              <set_value name="$XMP.ProxyWireIdByGameId.{$XMP.NewProxyShip.id}" exact="$XMP.RxObjectId" />

              <!-- Assumption (see file header): a proxy needs an assigned NPC pilot
                   before an AI-script can fly it. Defensive; may be unnecessary. -->
              <create_pilot name="$XMP.NewProxyPilot" ship="$XMP.NewProxyShip" race="argon" />

              <!-- A4: a proxy is a purely local visual stand-in for a REAL ship in
                   another player's game; it must never take (or deal) "real" local
                   damage, only the server-authoritative hp_state applies. -->
              <set_object_invulnerable object="$XMP.NewProxyShip" value="true" />

              <!-- Seed the blackboard with the spawn placement itself and zero
                   velocity, so Dead Reckoning starts from a valid, non-null state
                   instead of waiting for the first state_update. -->
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosX" exact="$XMP.NewProxyShip.position.x" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosY" exact="$XMP.NewProxyShip.position.y" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosZ" exact="$XMP.NewProxyShip.position.z" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelX" exact="0" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelY" exact="0" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelZ" exact="0" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.NewProxyShip.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime" exact="player.age" />

              <!-- Params passed here override the AI-script's own <param> defaults;
                   see XMP_Arena_TuningDefaults above for where these values live. -->
              <start_ai_script name="XMP.ProxyPilot" object="$XMP.NewProxyShip">
                <param name="$ExtrapolationHorizonSec" value="$XMP.DeadReckoningExtrapolationHorizonSec" />
                <param name="$SnapThresholdMeters" value="$XMP.DeadReckoningSnapThresholdMeters" />
                <param name="$UpdateTimeoutSec" value="$XMP.DeadReckoningUpdateTimeoutSec" />
                <param name="$RetargetIntervalSec" value="$XMP.DeadReckoningRetargetIntervalSec" />
              </start_ai_script>
              <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][Arena] spawned proxy for ' + $XMP.RxOwner + ' (objectId=' + $XMP.RxObjectId + ')'" filter="general" />
            </do_all>
            <else>
              <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][Arena] spawn for already-known objectId=' + $XMP.RxObjectId + ', ignoring'" filter="general" />
            </else>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      Removes a remote player's proxy (they disconnected, the server told us to, or,
      since A4, their ship was destroyed in combat). Teardown itself is shared with
      XMP_Arena_HandleHpState via XMP_Arena_DestroyProxy, since a combat kill and a
      disconnect/manual despawn need the exact same cleanup (AI-script, reverse
      lookup, Proxies table), differing only in whether an explosion plays.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_HandleDespawn" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'objectId'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxObjectId" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <do_if value="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.exists">
            <do_all>
              <set_value name="$XMP.DestroyObjectId" exact="$XMP.RxObjectId" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.DestroyExplosion" exact="false" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_DestroyProxy" />
              <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][Arena] despawned proxy objectId=' + $XMP.RxObjectId" filter="general" />
            </do_all>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      Since A3: no longer teleports position directly (that was the A2 baseline).
      Writes the latest known truth (position, velocity, receive time) onto the
      proxy's blackboard; aiscripts/XMP.ProxyPilot.xml running on that ship picks
      it up on its own next loop iteration and either extrapolates toward it or
      snap-teleports if the deviation is too large (see that file's header).
      Rotation is still applied immediately here, not extrapolated: PlanMod.md A3
      only calls for extrapolating POSITION via the velocity vector, and a rotation
      snap is far less visually jarring than a position teleport. Assumption on top
      of the existing "set_object_position accepts position+rotation together" one
      (see file header): passing only `rotation` without `position` still applies
      just the rotation, leaving position untouched.

      Also reads linkLatencyMs (added by the agent, agent/src/pipeMessage.ts, not
      part of the WebSocket/session wire schema) and backdates the blackboard's
      receive time by it, so the AI-script's "elapsed = now - recv time" math
      automatically compensates for network transit delay as well as time elapsed
      locally since (PlanMod.md A3 "Position + Geschwindigkeitsvektor x Latenz").
      Falls back to 0 (no backdating) if the field is missing (e.g. an older
      agent version), guarded by checking the extractor actually found it.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_HandleStateUpdate" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'shipId'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxObjectId" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <do_if value="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.exists">
            <do_all>
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'position'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxPositionJson" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'rotation'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxRotationJson" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'velocity'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxVelocityJson" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

              <!-- linkLatencyMs (see cue header): read here, before $XMP.RxLine
                   gets reassigned to the position/rotation/velocity substrings
                   below, and before $XMP.ExtractKeyPos gets overwritten by the
                   next extraction call. Assumption: XMP_Arena_ExtractField's
                   underlying find_string leaves $XMP.ExtractKeyPos at -1 when the
                   key is not found at all (as opposed to throwing or erroring). -->
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'linkLatencyMs'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <do_if value="$XMP.ExtractKeyPos != -1">
                <set_value name="$XMP.RxLinkLatencyMs" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
                <else>
                  <set_value name="$XMP.RxLinkLatencyMs" exact="0" />
                </else>
              </do_if>

              <!-- Sub-extraction: position/rotation/velocity are nested objects, so
                   we run the same field extractor again against just their
                   substrings. -->
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxLine" exact="$XMP.RxPositionJson" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'x'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxPosX" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'y'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxPosY" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'z'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxPosZ" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />

              <set_value name="$XMP.RxLine" exact="$XMP.RxRotationJson" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'qx'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxRotQX" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'qy'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxRotQY" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'qz'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxRotQZ" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'qw'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxRotQW" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />

              <set_value name="$XMP.RxLine" exact="$XMP.RxVelocityJson" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'x'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxVelX" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'y'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxVelY" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'z'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxVelZ" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />

              <set_object_position
                object="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}"
                rotation="table[x=$XMP.RxRotQX, y=$XMP.RxRotQY, z=$XMP.RxRotQZ, w=$XMP.RxRotQW]" />

              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosX" exact="$XMP.RxPosX" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosY" exact="$XMP.RxPosY" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetPosZ" exact="$XMP.RxPosZ" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelX" exact="$XMP.RxVelX" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelY" exact="$XMP.RxVelY" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetVelZ" exact="$XMP.RxVelZ" />
              <!-- Backdated by the estimated one-way link latency (see cue header
                   above); this is what makes the AI-script's plain "now minus recv
                   time" extrapolation implement "Position + Geschwindigkeitsvektor
                   x Latenz" without any latency-specific code in the AI-script. -->
              <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_TargetRecvTime"
                exact="player.age - ($XMP.RxLinkLatencyMs / 1000)" />
            </do_all>
            <else>
              <!-- We haven't seen a spawn for this objectId yet (e.g. we joined mid-session
                   before the spawn replay arrived); drop the update, nothing to move. -->
            </else>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      A4: shared proxy teardown, used by both XMP_Arena_HandleDespawn (disconnect/
      manual despawn, no explosion) and XMP_Arena_HandleHpState (combat kill, with
      explosion). Callers set $XMP.DestroyObjectId (wire objectId) and
      $XMP.DestroyExplosion (true/false) before including this cue.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_DestroyProxy" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.DestroyGameId" exact="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.DestroyObjectId}.id" />
          <stop_ai_script name="XMP.ProxyPilot" object="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.DestroyObjectId}" />
          <destroy_object object="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.DestroyObjectId}" explosion="$XMP.DestroyExplosion" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.DestroyObjectId}" exact="null" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.ProxyWireIdByGameId.{$XMP.DestroyGameId}" exact="null" />
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      A4: applies a server-authoritative hp_state to whichever local representation
      of that objectId we have. Two cases:
        - Our OWN ship (objectId == player.entity.id): a materially real change to
          the player's actual ship, since the server round-trip is what confirmed
          it actually happened (client-side hit detection only ever REPORTS a hit,
          never resolves it; see PlanMod.md A4's accepted client-side-hit-
          detection weakness, documented in the file header and
          docs/A4-messprotokoll.md).
        - A remote player's proxy: the proxy is invulnerable (XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn),
          so there is no "real" hull/shield to update on it; the value is tracked on
          its blackboard only for possible future display purposes (no health bar
          exists yet). Either way, hull reaching 0 triggers the destruction
          sequence via XMP_Arena_DestroyProxy (proxy) or a direct destroy_object
          (own ship).
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_HandleHpState" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'objectId'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxObjectId" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'hull'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxHull" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />

          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'shield'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxShield" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue.{tonumber}" />

          <do_if value="player.entity.exists and $XMP.RxObjectId == player.entity.id">
            <do_all>
              <set_object_hull object="player.entity" exact="$XMP.RxHull" />
              <set_object_shield object="player.entity" exact="$XMP.RxShield" />
              <do_if value="$XMP.RxHull &lt;= 0">
                <do_all>
                  <destroy_object object="player.entity" explosion="true" />
                  <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][Arena] our own ship was destroyed (server-confirmed)'" filter="general" />
                </do_all>
              </do_if>
            </do_all>
            <else>
              <do_if value="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.exists">
                <do_all>
                  <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_DisplayHull" exact="$XMP.RxHull" />
                  <set_value name="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.blackboard.$XMP_DisplayShield" exact="$XMP.RxShield" />
                  <do_if value="$XMP.RxHull &lt;= 0">
                    <do_all>
                      <set_value name="$XMP.DestroyObjectId" exact="$XMP.RxObjectId" />
                      <set_value name="$XMP.DestroyExplosion" exact="true" />
                      <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_DestroyProxy" />
                      <debug_text text="'[XMultiplayer][Arena] proxy objectId=' + $XMP.RxObjectId + ' destroyed (server-confirmed)'" filter="general" />
                    </do_all>
                  </do_if>
                </do_all>
              </do_if>
            </else>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      A4: cosmetic-only. Plays a fake weapon effect on the corresponding proxy so
      it visually looks like it's firing back; never applies any damage locally
      (real damage only ever arrives via hp_state). Silently does nothing if we
      don't have a proxy for sourceId (e.g. a state_update/spawn race, or the
      shooter despawned between firing and this arriving).
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_HandleFireEvent" instantiate="false">
      <actions>
        <do_all>
          <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'sourceId'" />
          <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
          <set_value name="$XMP.RxObjectId" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />

          <do_if value="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}.exists">
            <do_all>
              <set_value name="$XMP.ExtractKey" exact="'weapon'" />
              <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Arena_ExtractField" />
              <set_value name="$XMP.RxWeapon" exact="$XMP.ExtractValue" />
              <fire_weapon_cosmetic object="$XMP.Proxies.{$XMP.RxObjectId}" weapon="$XMP.RxWeapon" />
            </do_all>
          </do_if>
        </do_all>
      </actions>
    </cue>

    <!--
      A4: local hit detection. Fires (assumption, see file header) whenever ANY
      object in the universe is attacked, including an invulnerable one, which is
      exactly why this exists instead of watching hull/shield for changes (those
      never move on an invulnerable proxy). Filters to objects we actually track as
      proxies via the reverse lookup populated in XMP_Arena_HandleSpawn, then
      reports the hit to the server; the server (not this client) decides what
      actually happens to the target's HP.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_OnProxyAttacked" instantiate="true">
      <conditions>
        <event_object_attacked />
      </conditions>
      <actions>
        <do_if value="$XMP.ProxyWireIdByGameId.{event.object.id}.exists">
          <do_all>
            <set_value name="$XMP.Json"
              exact="'{&quot;v&quot;:1,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;hit_report&quot;,&quot;seq&quot;:0,&quot;ts&quot;:' + player.age
                + ',&quot;targetId&quot;:&quot;' + $XMP.ProxyWireIdByGameId.{event.object.id} + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;sourceId&quot;:&quot;' + player.entity.id + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;damage&quot;:' + event.param
                + ',&quot;damageType&quot;:&quot;' + event.param2 + '&quot;'
                + '}'" />
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Telemetry_WriteToPipe" />
          </do_all>
        </do_if>
      </actions>
      <cues>
        <cue name="XMP_Arena_OnProxyAttacked_Reset" instantiate="true">
          <conditions>
            <cue_completed cue="parent" />
          </conditions>
          <actions>
            <reset_cue cue="parent" />
          </actions>
        </cue>
      </cues>
    </cue>

    <!--
      A4: local outgoing fire detection, scoped to our own ship only. Builds the
      fire_event other clients use to play a cosmetic effect on our proxy in their
      games (XMP_Arena_HandleFireEvent). Never carries any damage information;
      damage only ever flows via hit_report/hp_state, this is purely for the other
      side's eyes.
    -->
    <cue name="XMP_Arena_OnOwnWeaponFired" instantiate="true">
      <conditions>
        <event_object_fired object="player.entity" />
      </conditions>
      <actions>
        <do_if value="player.entity.exists and player.entity.isclass.ship">
          <do_all>
            <set_value name="$XMP.Json"
              exact="'{&quot;v&quot;:1,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;fire_event&quot;,&quot;seq&quot;:0,&quot;ts&quot;:' + player.age
                + ',&quot;sourceId&quot;:&quot;' + player.entity.id + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;weapon&quot;:&quot;' + event.param + '&quot;'
                + ',&quot;origin&quot;:{&quot;x&quot;:' + player.entity.position.x + ',&quot;y&quot;:' + player.entity.position.y + ',&quot;z&quot;:' + player.entity.position.z + '}'
                + ',&quot;direction&quot;:{&quot;x&quot;:' + event.param2.x + ',&quot;y&quot;:' + event.param2.y + ',&quot;z&quot;:' + event.param2.z + '}'
                + '}'" />
            <include_interrupt_actions ref="XMP_Telemetry_WriteToPipe" />
          </do_all>
        </do_if>
      </actions>
      <cues>
        <cue name="XMP_Arena_OnOwnWeaponFired_Reset" instantiate="true">
          <conditions>
            <cue_completed cue="parent" />
          </conditions>
          <actions>
            <reset_cue cue="parent" />
          </actions>
        </cue>
      </cues>
    </cue>
  </cues>
</mdscript>
